This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing and parsing. The use of machine learning techniques such as multi-task learning and policy gradient also suggests that it could belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper addresses issues of error rates and sparsity, which are common challenges in artificial intelligence and could place it in the sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper mentions the use of auxiliary losses and sentence-level fine-tuning, which are techniques commonly used in computer vision, suggesting that it could also belong to the sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision).
